The paper deals with the problem of integrating heterogeneous data (such as acoustic and visual content) into a single similarity space, which is a common challenge in multimedia applications. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV), Information Retrieval (cs.IR), and Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper proposes a novel multiple kernel learning technique, which is a machine learning method, indicating that it could also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions the use of graph-based techniques, which are commonly used in Natural Language Processing (cs.CL), suggesting that this sub-category is also a possibility.
